  "local_port": 57352,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some things new employees should know going into their first day at AIG?",
  "response": "Starting a new role at AIG can be exciting, and being prepared with key insights will help ensure a smooth transition. Here\u2019s a structured guide for new employees:\n\n### 1. **Company Culture**\n   - **Core Values**: AIG emphasizes integrity, collaboration, innovation, and client focus. Familiarize yourself with their mission statement and values, which underpin decision-making and interactions.\n   - **Dress Code**: Typically business professional, but this may vary by department (e.g., corporate vs. tech roles). Confirm with your manager.\n   - **Inclusivity**: AIG prioritizes diversity and inclusion, offering Employee Resource Groups (ERGs) and initiatives to foster belonging.\n\n### 2. **Onboarding Process**\n   - **Paperwork**: Expect HR forms (tax, benefits) and IT setup (laptop, email, access to systems like Workday or Salesforce).\n   - **Orientation**: Likely includes a company overview, office tour, and introductions to your team and key stakeholders.\n\n### 3. **Team Structure & Role Clarity**\n   - **Key Contacts**: Identify your manager, team members, and cross-functional partners. Learn how your role contributes to AIG\u2019s goals (e.g., underwriting, claims, risk management).\n   - **Stakeholders**: Note internal clients (e.g., actuarial, legal) and external partners (brokers, clients).\n\n### 4. **Training & Development**\n   - **Mandatory Training**: Compliance, ethics, and regulatory modules (e.g., GDPR, anti-money laundering).\n   - **Professional Growth**: Explore mentorship programs, LinkedIn Learning access, or tuition reimbursement for industry certifications (e.g., CPCU, ARM).\n\n### 5. **Policies & Procedures**\n   - **Remote/Hybrid Work**: Understand your team\u2019s norms for in-office days and flexible hours.\n   - **Time Off**: Learn procedures for vacation, sick leave, and AIG\u2019s holiday schedule.\n   - **Expenses & Travel**: Review policies for submitting expenses or booking travel.\n\n### 6. **Technology & Tools**\n   - **Software**: Master tools like Microsoft 365, Teams, Zoom, and proprietary systems (e.g., underwriting platforms).\n   - **IT Support**: Save the helpdesk contact for troubleshooting.\n\n### 7. **Networking & Relationships**\n   - **Meet Colleagues**: Attend team lunches or virtual coffee chats. Join ERGs or committees to expand your network.\n   - **Industry Knowledge**: Follow insurance trends (e.g., insurtech, climate risk) to engage in meaningful conversations.\n\n### 8. **Performance Expectations**\n   - **Goals**: Clarify 30/60/90-day objectives and key metrics (e.g., client retention, claims processing efficiency).\n   - **Feedback**: AIG often uses structured reviews. Ask about feedback frequency and channels.\n\n### 9. **Company History & Market Position**\n   - **Legacy**: AIG\u2019s 100+ year history includes navigating challenges like the 2008 crisis. Understand its evolution and current strategy (e.g., digital transformation).\n   - **Differentiators**: Learn how AIG competes through innovation (e.g., AI-driven underwriting) or global reach (operations in 80+ countries).\n\n### 10. **Benefits & Perks**\n   - **Health & Wellness**: Comprehensive medical plans, mental health resources, and wellness programs.\n   - **Retirement**: 401(k) matching and financial planning tools.\n   - **Discounts**: Access to insurance products, gym memberships, or retail partnerships.\n\n### 11. **Communication Channels**\n   - **Internal Updates**: Use platforms like SharePoint or intranet for company news. Attend town halls for leadership insights.\n   - **Team Dynamics**: Note preferred communication styles (e.g., Slack for quick questions, email for formal requests).\n\n### 12. **Global Mindset**\n   - **Cross-Cultural Collaboration**: Be mindful of time zones and cultural nuances when working with international teams.\n   - **Regulatory Awareness**: Understand regional regulations affecting your role (e.g., Solvency II in Europe).\n\n### 13. **Compliance & Ethics**\n   - **Risk Management**: Adhere to strict guidelines in handling client data and financial transactions.\n   - **Whistleblower Policies**: Know how to report concerns confidentially.\n\n### 14. **Emergency Protocols**\n   - **Safety**: Locate emergency exits, first-aid kits, and evacuation routes. Register for alerts via AIG\u2019s security system.\n\n### 15. **Pro Tips for Day One**\n   - **Arrive Early**: Allow time for unexpected delays.\n   - **Ask Questions**: No query is too small\u2014whether about workflows or where to find supplies.\n   - **Stay Curious**: Take notes during onboarding and shadow colleagues to learn faster.\n\nBy focusing on these areas, you\u2019ll navigate your first day with confidence and set the stage for long-term success at AIG. Welcome to the team! \ud83d\ude80",
